    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A planetary conjunction, not to be confused with a collision, is actually when two or more celestial bodies appear to be aligned in the same direction, but they're not necessarily physically touching. This occurs when the planets are in the same orbital plane, but their positions are such that they form a straight line in the sky. Think of it like a row of ships passing through the night sky, where the planets are just passing each other by, not actually colliding. The reason they don't always hit each other is due to their vast distances and orbital velocities.",
